# Shared Layouts

Often you want a common layout (header, sidebar) that persists across multiple pages. React Router lets you nest routes, so a parent route can render a layout and then an `<Outlet />` where child routes render.

## Example

```jsx
import { Routes, Route, Outlet } from 'react-router-dom';

function Layout() {
  return (
    <div>
      <header>My Site</header>
      <Outlet />  {/* Child routes render here */}
    </div>
  );
}

function App() {
  return (
    <Routes>
      <Route path="/" element={<Layout />}>
        <Route index element={<Home />} />
        <Route path="about" element={<About />} />
        <Route path="contact" element={<Contact />} />
      </Route>
    </Routes>
  );
}
```

The `index` route means the default child when the parent path matches exactly.

